# The Kubernetes namespace where Kafka and Debezium are deployed
kubernetes.namespace=be-test

### The Absolute Must-Have: Kubernetes RBAC

For your Spring Boot backend to be allowed to "talk" to Kubernetes (to scale pods and read logs), your DevOps team **must** assign a Role to the Spring Boot Pod. 

Give this exactly to your DevOps team:

> *"Can you please apply this Role and RoleBinding to the ServiceAccount used by the Notification Service Backend in Tanzu? It needs permission to check status, restart, and view logs of Debezium."*

```yaml
apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: Role
metadata:
  namespace: be-test
  name: notification-admin-role
rules:
- apiGroups: ["apps"]
  resources: ["deployments", "deployments/scale"]
  verbs: ["get", "list", "watch", "patch", "update"]
- apiGroups: [""]
  resources: ["pods", "pods/log"]
  verbs: ["get", "list", "watch"]
---
apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: RoleBinding
metadata:
  name: notification-admin-rolebinding
  namespace: be-test
subjects:
- kind: ServiceAccount
  name: default # Change this if your Backend uses a specific service account name
  namespace: be-test
roleRef:
  kind: Role
  name: notification-admin-role
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io

### Summary of this approach:
1. **Highly Flexible:** Because you use the Kubernetes API instead of Kafka Connect, it doesn't matter what URLs are configured for Dev vs. Prod. Debezium will just use whatever ConfigMap DevOps gave it.
2. **Safe:** You are scaling the Deployment up and down (0 or 1). This is the safest way to pause Debezium in Kubernetes because it gracefully stops reading from Oracle and commits offsets to Kafka.
3. **Easy for Frontend:** The frontend simply creates buttons for "Start", "Stop", "Restart" and a text box for Logs, calling the REST APIs above!













